{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657495"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:29:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:29:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20502"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20502"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13375"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92609"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13375"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20502"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75949"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11582"},{"type":"tags","id":"11753"},{"type":"tags","id":"12434"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31732"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31733"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92609"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EExogenous pigments are foreign substances that can accumulate in human tissues. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathophysiology of exogenous pigment accumulation in tissues?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pigments bind to nuclear DNA causing cellular mutations","Pigments directly damage cell membranes causing necrosis","Pigments dissolve in cytoplasm causing cellular swelling","Pigments are phagocytosed by macrophages and stored long-term","Pigments stimulate autoimmune reactions against host tissues"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that \u003Cstrong\u003Epigments are phagocytosed by macrophages and stored long-term\u003C/strong\u003E. This is the primary pathophysiological mechanism for exogenous pigment accumulation in tissues. For example, carbon dust in the lungs is engulfed by alveolar macrophages and transported to regional lymph nodes where it remains. Similarly, tattoo pigments are phagocytosed by dermal macrophages and typically remain there for the person\u0027s lifetime.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPigments directly damage cell membranes causing necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E - Most exogenous pigments like carbon dust or tattoo ink do not directly cause cell membrane damage or necrosis. They are relatively inert once phagocytosed.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPigments bind to nuclear DNA causing cellular mutations\u003C/strong\u003E - Exogenous pigments typically remain within macrophage lysosomes and do not interact with nuclear DNA to cause mutations.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPigments stimulate autoimmune reactions against host tissues\u003C/strong\u003E - Most exogenous pigments like carbon dust and tattoo ink typically do not evoke significant inflammatory or autoimmune responses.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPigments dissolve in cytoplasm causing cellular swelling\u003C/strong\u003E - Rather than dissolving in cytoplasm, exogenous pigments are contained within phagolysosomes of macrophages.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe accumulation of carbon dust in lungs leads to anthracosis (blackening of lung tissue). In coal miners, excessive exposure can progress to coal worker\u0027s pneumoconiosis, characterized by fibroblastic reactions or emphysema, resulting in serious lung disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Carbon (coal dust) is the most common exogenous pigment that can accumulate in lung tissue and regional lymph nodes.","Anthracosis refers to blackening of lung tissue due to carbon dust accumulation.","Exogenous pigments are phagocytosed by macrophages and typically remain in tissues for long periods."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. p. 64."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75949"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20502"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75949"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-18T14:52:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-18T14:53:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13375"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92609"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11582"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Cell injury, cell death and adaptations","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":1,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:12:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:12:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11753","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11753"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Intracellular accumulations","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-0